'''Sumbat Davitis Dze''' ({{lang-ka|სუმბატ დავითის ძე}}), or '''Sumbat, son of David''', in modern English transliteration, was the 11th-century [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] chronicler who described in his ''The Life and Tale of the Bagratids'' the history of the [[Bagrationi dynasty]] of Georgia from the beginnings until c. 1030. The Georgian scholar [[Ekvtime Takaishvili]] has demonstrated that Sumbat belonged to that dynasty. The author is notable for his articulation of the Bagratid [[Claim of the biblical descent of the Bagrationi dynasty|claim to be descended]] from the biblical King-Prophet [[David]].
