{{Infobox UN resolution |number = 369 |organ = SC |date = 28 May |year = 1975 |meeting = 1,822 |code = S/RES/369 |document = https://undocs.org/S/RES/369(1975) |for = 13 |abstention = 0 |against = 0 |subject = Israel-Syria |result = Adopted |image = Middle East (orthographic projection).svg |caption = The Middle East }}
'''[[United Nations]] [[List of UN Security Council Resolutions|Security Council Resolution]] 369''', adopted on May 28, 1975, expressed concern over the prevailing state of tensions between Israel and Syria and reaffirmed that the two previous agreements on disengagements of forces were only a step towards the implementation of [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 338|resolution 338]]. The resolution then decided to call upon the parties concerned to immediately implement resolution 338, renewed the mandate of the [[United Nations Disengagement Observer Force Zone|United Nations Disengagement Observer Force]] for another 6 months and requested the [[United Nations Secretary-General|Secretary-General]] submit a report on the situation at the end of those 6 months.
The resolution was adopted by 13 votes; [[People's Republic of China|China]] and [[Iraq]] did not participate in the vote.
